[2]
Date: Sat, 14 Sep 2002 07:42:37 -0400
From: Eleanor Kellon VMD <kell@epix.net>


I've been following the spread of this virus since the first cases emerged
in 1999, both intra- and interstate. From the New York epicenter, there
was concentric spread up and down the coast, while the virus on the
mainland worked its way up the Hudson River for the most part, with the
counties falling like dominoes from south to north. While certainly
inadvertent mechanical movement could play a role, the pattern of spread
has largely remained contiguous, from one area into an immediately
adjoining one.

Factors such as surveillance intensity, density of horses, density of
fatally affected avian species (or density of people around to find them),
etc., give a bit of a patchwork pattern to it, but the overall pattern
remains from east to west and both north and south from the epicenter.

The influence of either nonmigratory birds or heavy local mosquito density
also shows up in some locations. For example, in Wyoming, there is a
cluster of equine cases (18) in the county of Goshen, which directly
borders on the most heavily affected Nebraska county of Scotts Bluff (75
cases). In fact, 4 of the 6 Wyoming counties where viral activity has been
detected are clustered around this area, all neighboring Goshen county to
the north, south, and west, with Scott's Bluff to the east. The most
distinguishing feature of Scott's Bluff [see URL below for map] is an
exceptionally heavy network of waterways. A key element of the
epidemiology may very well be the species of birds that are not fatally
infected and are responsible for keeping the virus in circulation and
moving it locally.
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/united_states/nebraska_1990.jpg>

Weather patterns also appear to be very important. States that have
experienced a heavy number of equine cases prior to the traditional heavy
encephalitis season of very late August into September and October have all
had torrential rains and flooding as an antecedent factor.

If the CA woman did acquire the virus from local infected mosquitos, a good
place to start looking for them may very well be the 200-acre bird
sanctuary located within 5 minutes of Los Angeles International
Airport. Marsh/sea birds like the wood stork, which migrates between
Mexico and the US, commingle in Mexico, then split into 2 groups, the
larger of which goes to Texas and the Gulf states, with a few birds
branching over into southern California. Migrating storks have been
strongly suspected as being involved in intercontinental spread of West Nile:

<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol7no3_supp/pdf/malkinson.pdf>

<http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/432144?WebLogicSession=PYMf42gkBXd2fOQGt2DXgcBB0UAHHbiueY2D3TKsOapsTVJcTsCH|7590257876527903150/184161394/6/7001/7001/7002/7002/7001/-1>

<http://www.oevr.org/ArticoliOsservatorio/1999-1/English/westnile_eng.htm>

and of hosting new and more neuroinvasive strains:

<http://www.pasteur.fr/applications/dri/English/DI/01.17.html>

---
Eleanor Kellon, V.M.D.
Horse Journal
<kell@epix.net>

