[3]
Date: Sun, 15 Sep 2002 14:44:52 +0100
From: Conor Kretsch <Conor.Kretsch@enviros.com>


Note that although the migration patterns of bird species are pretty well
defined, the movements of individual birds are entirely unpredictable.

It would not be surprising if one or more birds have crossed from east to
west, north to south, or any combination outside of normal migration
routes. Random movements are not uncommon, particularly for raptors,
seabirds, waders, and waterfowl. Also it is not necessarily true that a
bird raised on the east coast will instinctively return there year after
year; the vast majority do, but not all. In fact, young birds in particular
can and frequently do explore new routes or travel vast distances to find
new territories, or simply get lost or blown off course. Extreme conditions
such as drought or flooding will increase the numbers that move outside of
the normal migration patterns. Wide mountain ranges and vast expanses of
water are no obstacle or deterrent to many species.

In addition, there are literally thousands of records each year of birds
turning up somewhere they 'shouldn't' be, again most often due to birds
getting lost or swept off-course by wind currents. Transatlantic,
transcontinental, and transpacific crossings by birds in this manner are a
common annual occurrence; though the numbers are relatively small, they are
larger than expected and certainly greater than recorded.

Consider occurrences of WNV infection in Italy attributed to the Senegal
strain, or other cases of WNV infection or seropositivity in France,
Portugal, Spain, and Romania. Migratory birds certainly may further the
spread of a disease across vast distances, and it does not depend on
individual birds travelling the full distance; a stepping-stone or
relay-type scenario is entirely possible. This makes the length of time a
bird or group of birds will survive with infection not such a limiting factor.

Consider also the fact that WNV was detected in crows in New York in late
1998. It should be surprising if the disease has not spread to California
by now -- some 2 and a half years later.

Regarding other vertebrates, I wonder whether there have been any recent
movements of potential reservoir/carrier species between zoos or private
collections across the US that might be implicated? I suspect that WNV is
indeed present in many more areas than so far detected.

--
Conor E Kretsch
Consultant Environmental Scientist
Enviros
4 The Plaza,
Swords, Co. Dublin, Ireland
<Conor.Kretsch@enviros.com>

