Date: Sat 14 Sep 2002 11:34 AM
From: Stephen M. Apatow <s.m.apatow@humanitarian.net>


In an effort to highlight the geographic and epidemiological impact of West
Nile Virus, I put together the following overview that can be accessed from
the Emerging Infectious Disease Network: West Nile Virus web site
<http://www.humanitarian.net/eidnet/wnv>:

14 Sep 2002 - WEST NILE VIRUS: BIODEFENSE AND EPIDEMIOLOGICAL TRACKING

Includes comparative maps of spread from 1999-2002 and current (as of 11
Sep 2002) USGS United States maps for bird, human, mosquito, sentinel, and
veterinary cases (note where there have been no reports or samples submitted).

<http://www.humanitarian.net/eidnet/wnv/wnv_biodefense.html>
[The CDC county-based chloropleth maps are outstanding!]

It would be interesting to compare the various strains isolated in global
regions prior to the 1999 outbreak. I would think that if the strain now
in the US is structurally different, then it could be (1) a result of a
mutation that accidentally found its way to the United States or (2) a
direct result of bioengineering.

A note regarding a reference to the WNV strain: I just ran across this
release by USGS/Department of the Interior:

14 Dec 1999
West Nile Virus May Be New Deadly Strain, USGS Tells Congress
<http://www.usgs.gov/public/press/public_affairs/press_releases/pr1128m.html>

[In this report, McLean is reported as saying: "Recent crow die-offs
suggest the West Nile virus, which emerged in New York in late August,
could be more deadly to North American bird species than to species in
Africa, the Middle East, and Europe, where the virus is normally found, a
USGS scientist reported today at a congressional field hearing held in
Connecticut by the Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works.

Dr. Robert G. McLean, director of the USGS National Wildlife Health Center
in Madison, Wis., briefed the committee on the role of native bird
populations and other wildlife in the emergence of West Nile virus in the
United States. Detection of the virus in birds and other animal species
provides critical information to public health agencies tracking the
infection in people.

'The high mortality in crows and other bird species is unusual for these
viruses,' McLean said. "This suggests that this virus is more virulent to
our native birds or it may represent a new, more virulent strain of the
virus."]

Bob McLean was a contact point for USGS, always helpful and an excellent
resource. As always, it looks like there is more to the picture than meets
the eye.

--
Stephen M. Apatow
Humanitarian Resource Institute
Biodefense Reference Library
<http://www.humanitarian.net/biodefense>
<s.m.apatow@humanitarian.net>

[Yes, a few birds do get lost and end up in the wrong place. But consider
the odds of one or 2 lost WNV-incubating birds being able to start an
outbreak in a new place. Modelling requires a lot more than
that. Stepping-stone or relay transmission is also stretching plausibility
-- since it requires a week or so for a mosquito, after taking an infected
blood meal, to produce infectious saliva, thatÂ´s postulating local
outbreaks at multiple stopovers en route. The most likely scenario is
still importations along mass-migration routes, which are not East-West and
-- assuming Mexico is in fact infected -- the South-North migration from
Mexico to California had not yet started in early August 2002, when the
California case was infected. As for the US WNV strain being more
virulent, it is not at all surprising to find unexposed populations of
vertebrates dying from the first introduction of a normally relatively
benign virus. Think myxomatosis in Australian rabbits, or measles in
Amazonian Indians, who had never been exposed to it before. - Mod.JW]

[I suspect we are coming to the end of productive comments on this topic
until critical research can clarify the various excellent points raised. I
am willing to consider one more posting on this subject, otherwise the
thread is being cut. - Mod.MHJ]
